  "variables": {
    "U": {
      "description": "Utility of accepting the offer",
      "range": {
        "min": "-inf",
        "max": "inf"
      },
      "learnable": false,
      "source": "calculated"
    },
    "alpha": {
      "description": "Weight on fairness considerations",
      "range": {
        "min": 0,
        "max": 10
      },
      "learnable": true,
      "source": "learnable"
    },
    "lambda_param": {
      "description": "Loss aversion parameter",
      "range": {
        "min": 0,
        "max": 10
      },
      "learnable": true,
      "source": "learnable"
    },
    "beta": {
      "description": "Baseline utility (inherent acceptance/rejection bias)",
      "range": {
        "min": -10,
        "max": 10
      },
      "learnable": true,
      "source": "learnable"
    },
    "split_self": {
      "description": "Amount offered to the responder",
      "range": {
        "min": 0,
        "max": "inf"
      },
      "learnable": false,
      "source": "data"
    },
    "combined_earning": {
      "description": "Total amount to be split",
      "range": {
        "min": 0,
        "max": "inf"
      },
      "learnable": false,
      "source": "data"
    },
    "token_self": {
      "description": "Number of tokens found by the responder",
      "range": {
        "min": 0,
        "max": "inf"
      },
      "learnable": false,
      "source": "data"
    },
    "token_opp": {
      "description": "Number of tokens found by the proposer",
      "range": {
        "min": 0,
        "max": "inf"
      },
      "learnable": false,
      "source": "data"
    }
  }
}
</VARIABLES>

<target_variable>accept</target_variable>

<SUMMARY>
A utility model for responder behavior in the ultimatum game. The model incorporates fairness considerations based on relative contributions, loss aversion for offers below the equitable split, and a baseline acceptance bias. Three learnable parameters (alpha, lambda_param, and beta) capture the weight of fairness, sensitivity to loss, and inherent acceptance tendency, respectively. Utility is a linear combination of these factors.
</SUMMARY>

